The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Wednesday, December 31, 2003  Nation at a Glance				 																Valley peace vow on New Years Day				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): Over 60,000 people are expected to attend a peace rally on New Years Day to press for an end to the 13-year-long militancy and reopening of roadlinks between Jammu and Kashmir and Pakistan-occupied Kashmir.				 																																																										The peace march, to be led by chief minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, will demonstrate that dominant sentiment in the state is that of peace and settlement, state revenue, relief and rehabilitation minister Hakeem Mohmmad Yasin said on Tuesday.				 																																																										Over 60,000 people are expected to throng the Kashmir peace rally, organised by all the partners of the coalition government at Srinagar on January 1, which will pass a message of peace, end to bloodshed, reopening of roadlinks and solving the Kashmir problem permanently to the Saarc conference in Islamabad, Yasin, a Peoples Democratic Party leader, said.				 																																																										Yasin said the rally is aimed at giving further fillip to the ongoing peace initiatives between India and Pakistan, which are now serious in solving the Kashmir issue to end bloodshed and help early return of peace and normalcy to the state.				 																Corruption charge on Farooq kin Jammu (PTI): A case has been registered  against Mustafa Kamal, former minister and brother of former  chief minister Farooq Abdullah, under the Prevention of  Corruption Act. In an FIR, the Jammu and Kashmir vigilance department  said on Monday: Pragati Bhavan, a commercial complex, was  allotted in favour of the Madre-e-Meharban Institute of  Health Sciences, Jammu, on a monthly rent of Rs 1.25 lakh  against a rent of Rs 2.5 lakh charged earlier from the management  of KHN Hospital by the Jammu Development Authority.				 																																																										An FIR has also been registered against the then vice-chairman of the Jammu Development Authority, Mohammad Aslam Qureshi, and others.				 																																																										A vigilance spokesperson said the board of directors of the development authority subsequently approved a monthly rent of Rs 1.25 lakh for the basement, ground and first floors of the complex.				 																																																										The institute, headed by Kamal, illegally occupied the remaining portion of the building against an advanced payment of Rs 3.75 lakh, in connivance with Qureshi, the spokesperson added.				 																Builder in bribe net				 																																																	Lucknow (PTI): A prominent city builder has been arrested for allegedly trying to bribe an IAS officer to scuttle a probe into a land deal, official sources said on Tuesday.				 																																																										Sunil Kumar Verma, managing director of Patel Colonisers, was arrested when he went to the residence of Anurag Yadav, a probationary IAS officer, allegedly to offer a bribe of Rs 1 lakh. Superintendent of police (west) S.C. Vajpayee said Verma wanted to convert a gram sabha land into free hold plots. 				 																Lashkar men killed				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): The army on Tuesday shot dead three Pakistani militants belonging to the Lashkar-e-Toiba in the Chingus forest belt of Rajouri district, sources said. The rebels opened fire and lobbed grenades when the army launched a pre-dawn operation to track them down. The militants, identified as Abu Asrar, Abu Talah and Abu Sigir, were killed in the retaliatory fire.				 																Councillor assault				 																																																	Madurai (PTI): A city corporation councillor was assaulted by councillors belonging to his party  the ADMK  for making an allegation against party MLA Seenivelu. The councillor alleged that the MLA was threatening to kill him following differences over drilling bore wells.				 																Teachers released				 																																																	Nawada (PTI): The headmaster and an assistant teacher of a high school were released on Tuesday after 20 days in captivity in Bihars Nawada district, police said. Sources said no ransom was paid for the release of headmaster Aditya Singh and assistant teacher Shailendra Singh of Baapu High School.				 																Infant death probe				 																																																	Jaipur (PTI): The Rajasthan womens commission has ordered a probe into the deaths of 11 infants in a government-run childrens home here. A three-member panel will conduct the inquiry. The deaths occurred over a period of three months.				 																Ex-sarpanch shot				 																																																	Hissar (PTI): A former sarpanch of Kanwari village in the district, Mahabir, was shot dead by some unidentified assailants. Mahabir, involved in crimes like murder and kidnapping, was on parole. 																		Three Congress workers, Kulfi Thangaraj, Bharati, both 30, and 27-year-old Ramesh Babu, have donated, perhaps for the first time in the country, their entire bodies to the medical college hospital in Coimbatore. All of them are bachelors.
